`.` is the CTX project root: a Rust workspace (`crates/`) implementing
the context-generation/verification system, plus everything around it —
docs, CI scripts, prompts-adjacent agent adapters, sandboxing config, and
a distributable `template/` scaffold that ships a subset of this
tooling into consumer projects.

The core dependency chain runs `ctx-scan` (writes `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx`
mirror-path files and stale-checks them) → `ctx-summarize` (generates
them, calling out to `agents/`'s stdin/stdout model adapter) →
`ctx-context` (serves/renders them, fails open per architectural
invariant) → `ctx-verify` (gates via `scripts/`'s FAIL-line checks,
fails closed). `ctx-status` and `ctx-brief` share a second on-disk
contract, `docs/status.json` + `docs/STATUS.md`. Both contracts are
described in full in `crates/rollup.ctx` and `docs/rollup.ctx` — an
editor touching either format must update every reader/writer listed
there, not just the crate they're changing.

`template/` duplicates the `scripts/` contract (file-enumeration
convention, `FAIL:` format, marker-splice rules) into a separate
distribution tree via `update-template.sh`; the two script sets must be
kept in sync manually since there's no shared library, only convention.
`.cagevars.example.ctx` and `agents/` both bound the agent-execution
surface — `ctx-cage` sandboxes the process, `agents/` defines the
model I/O contract — but neither depends on the other in-tree.

Per root `intent.md`: Layer 1 (uncompilable-not-discouraged) is enforced
in `crates/` via shared lint/fake-seam patterns; Layer 2 (context before
source, drift-checked) is the `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` pipeline above.

intent_divergence: docs/rollup.ctx records that no validation gate exists
on summarizer output and drift between prompts and summaries goes
undetected, which is a live gap against the intent's Layer 2 claim that
context "cannot silently drift from the source."